    <exercise xml:id="exer_sec52-6">
      <statement>
        <p>
          For which natural numbers <m>n</m> is <m>n^2 \lt 2^n</m>?
          Justify your conclusion.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          If <m>n \geq 5</m>, then <m>n^2 \lt  2^n</m>.  To prove this, we let <m>P(n)</m> be 
          <m>n^2 \lt  2^n</m>.  For the basis step, when <m>n = 5</m>, <m>n^2 = 25</m>, 
          <m>2^n = 32</m>, and <m>25 \lt  32</m>.  For the inductive step, we assume that 
          <m>k \geq 5</m>  and that <m>P(k)</m> is true or that <m>k^2 \lt  2^k</m>.  
          With these assumptions, we need to prove that <m>P(k+1)</m> is true or that 
          <m>(k+1)^2 \lt  2^{k+1}</m>.  We first note that
          <me xml:id="exer42-2anseq">
            ( k + 1 )^2 = k^2 + 2k + 1 \lt  2^k + 2k + 1 \qquad (1)
          </me>.
          Since <m>k \geq 5</m>, we see that <m>5k \lt  k^2</m> and so <m>2k + 3k \lt  k^2</m>.  
          However, <m>3k > 1</m> and so <m>2k + 1 \lt  2k + 3k \lt  k^2</m>.  
          Combinining this with inequality (1), we obtain 
          <m>(k+1)^2 \lt  2^k+ k^2</m>. 
          Using the assumption that <m>P(k)</m> is true <m>\left(k^2 \lt  2^k\right)</m>, we obtain
          <md>
            <mrow>(k+1)^2 \amp \lt  2^k + 2^k = 2 \cdot 2^k</mrow>
            <mrow>(k+1)^2 \amp \lt  2^{k+1}</mrow>
          </md>
          This proves that if <m>P(k)</m> is true, then <m>P(k+1)</m> is true.
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>

